  "base_commit": "43b12311e6f4daea7c282212080394bec21e4bd8",
  "pr_number": 2354,
  "issue_number": 2353,
  "issue_title": "SyncJob silently discarded after Rails 8.1 upgrade (enqueue_after_transaction_commit race)",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nTwo latent regressions introduced by the alpha.6 Rails 7.2 \u2192 8.1 upgrade share a single root cause: ActiveJob's `enqueue_after_transaction_commit` default changed from \"defer until the transaction commits\" to \"enqueue immediately\". Any job enqueued inside a DB transaction can now be dequeued by a Sidekiq worker before `COMMIT`, on a separate connection that cannot see the uncommitted rows. This manifests as (1) silently discarded `SyncJob`s / stuck syncs, and (2) leaked SnapTrade brokerage connections on disconnect.\n\n## Shared root cause\n\n`enqueue_after_transaction_commit` controls whether a `perform_later` issued inside an Active Record transaction is deferred until that transaction commits.\n\n- Rails 7.2: `config.load_defaults 7.2` set `config.active_job.enqueue_after_transaction_commit = :default`, and the Sidekiq adapter (`AbstractAdapter#enqueue_after_transaction_commit?`) returned `true`, so in-transaction enqueues were deferred until commit. The race was covered by the default.\n- Rails 8.0: the `:always`/`:never`/`:default` enum was collapsed to a boolean `class_attribute` defaulting to `false` (`activejob/lib/active_job/enqueuing.rb`), and the global config toggle was deprecated.\n- Rails 8.1 (current): the global `config.active_job.enqueue_after_transaction_commit` toggle is non-functional \u2014 the Active Job railtie explicitly excludes the key from global application (\"This config can't be applied globally\"). Only the per-class `class_attribute` is honored, and it defaults to `false` (enqueue immediately). `raw_enqueue` defers via `ActiveRecord.after_all_transactions_commit` only when the attribute is truthy (`active_job/enqueue_after_transaction_commit.rb`).\n- Rails 8.2: the default flips back to `true`; the Active Job changelog states the reason directly \u2014 \"jobs would surprisingly run against uncommitted and rolled-back records.\"\n\n## Bug 1 \u2014 `SyncJob` silently discarded (stuck syncs)\n\n`Syncable#sync_later` (`app/models/concerns/syncable.rb:18`) opens `Sync.transaction` (`:19`), creates a `Sync` row, and calls `SyncJob.perform_later(sync)` (`:38`) inside that transaction. The job carries only a GlobalID reference to the not-yet-committed `Sync`.\n\nUnder the 8.1 default the enqueue is immediate, so a Sidekiq worker on another connection can dequeue before `COMMIT`, fail to resolve the `Sync` GlobalID, and raise `ActiveJob::DeserializationError`. `ApplicationJob` declares `discard_on ActiveJob::DeserializationError`, so the job is dropped without a trace \u2014 which is why the symptom is a silently stuck / never-completing sync rather than a visible error.\n\nReported in Discord by Alessio (the `SyncJob` discard with `ActiveJob::DeserializationError`) and Murphy (a stuck Enable Banking sync).\n\n## Bug 2 \u2014 SnapTrade / Indexa connection-cleanup leak\n\n`SnaptradeAccount` declares `after_destroy :enqueue_connection_cleanup` (`app/models/snaptrade_account.rb:24`), which enqueues `SnaptradeConnectionCleanupJob.perform_later(...)` (`:196`) from inside the destroy transaction. This is reached whenever a SnapTrade connection is removed, including the `SnaptradeItem has_many :snaptrade_accounts, dependent: :destroy` cascade (`app/models/snaptrade_item.rb:34`) triggered by `destroy_later` \u2192 `DestroyJob.perform_later` (`:45`, `:47`).\n\nThe cleanup job's idempotency guard checks whether a sibling account still uses the authorization \u2014 `snaptrade_item.snaptrade_accounts.where(snaptrade_authorization_id:).exists?` (`app/jobs/snaptrade_connection_cleanup_job.rb:27`) \u2014 and returns early (\"Skipping deletion\", `:32`) if so; otherwise it calls `provider.delete_connection(...)` (`:49`). Two failure modes under immediate enqueue:\n\n1. Stale read \u2192 leaked connection: a worker running before `COMMIT` sees the not-yet-deleted account row, the `exists?` guard returns a false positive, the job skips `provider.delete_connection`, and the SnapTrade brokerage authorization is left active at the provider even though the user disconnected.\n2. Rollback \u2192 orphaned external delete: if the destroy transaction rolls back after the worker already issued the irreversible `provider.delete_connection`, the local account/item still exists while the provider-side connection is gone.\n\n`IndexaCapitalAccount` has the identical wiring (`app/models/indexa_capital_account.rb:23` \u2192 `IndexaCapitalConnectionCleanupJob.perform_later`, `:94`) with the same shared-authorization guard, but its `delete_connection` is currently a TODO placeholder (no real provider call), so for Indexa the enqueue-timing race exists structurally while the provider leak is latent. Only SnapTrade is production-impacting today.\n\n## Related cleanup \u2014 `DestroyJob`\n\n`DestroyJob` (`app/jobs/destroy_job.rb`) set `self.enqueue_after_transaction_commit = :never`, the removed Rails 7.2 symbol API. Under 8.1's boolean attribute `:never` is truthy, so the job has been *deferring* by accident \u2014 dead, misleading config from the same migration. It is removed so the job inherits the (now correct) base-class policy; runtime behaviour is unchanged on 8.1.\n\n## Fix\n\nSet `self.enqueue_after_transaction_commit = true` on `ApplicationJob`. Because every job inherits from it and none override the attribute, this single change defers all in-transaction enqueues until commit (and drops them on rollback), fixing Bug 1, Bug 2, and any future in-transaction enqueue site at once. This adopts the Rails 8.2 default early. The fix must use the per-class `class_attribute` \u2014 `config.active_job.enqueue_after_transaction_commit` is silently ignored on 8.1 (see root cause). Also remove the dead `:never` override on `DestroyJob`.\n\n## Impact\n\n- Bug 1: any sync triggered via `sync_later` while a surrounding transaction is open (the common path); symptom is silently stuck syncs.\n- Bug 2: SnapTrade connection removal; symptom is a leaked brokerage authorization at the provider after the user disconnects.\n- Both introduced by the alpha.6 Rails 7.2 \u2192 8.1 upgrade.\n\n## Not related\n\nThe Enable Banking `WRONG_REQUEST_PARAMETERS` / PDNG warning is a separate pending-transaction issue and is not part of this.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-06-15T19:43:09.000Z",
